# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: e-coli
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:e-coli/biological-nomenclature] As the study of biology became increasingly specialized, specific codes were adopted for different types of organism.
[src:e-coli/biological-nomenclature] To an end-user who only deals with names of species, with some awareness that species are assignable to genera, families, and other taxa of higher ranks, it may not be noticeable that there is more than one code, but beyond this basic level these are rather different in the way they work.
[src:e-coli/biological-nomenclature] Such a name is called a **binomial name** (which may be shortened to just "binomial"), a **binomen**, **binominal name,** or a **scientific name**; more informally it is also historically called a **Latin name**.
[src:e-coli/biological-nomenclature] In the zoological code, ICZN, the system is also called **binominal nomenclature** (using the suffix *-inal* instead of *-ial*), meaning "two-name naming system".
[src:e-coli/biological-nomenclature] The first part of the name – the *generic name* – identifies the genus to which the species belongs, whereas the second part – the **specific name** or **specific epithet** – distinguishes the species within the genus.
[src:e-coli/biological-nomenclature] For example, modern humans belong to the genus *Homo* and within this genus to the species *Homo sapiens*.
[src:e-coli/biological-nomenclature] *Tyrannosaurus rex* is likely the most widely known non-human binomial.
[src:e-coli/biological-nomenclature] The *formal* introduction of this system of naming species is credited to Carl Linnaeus, effectively beginning with his work *Species Plantarum* in 1753.
[src:e-coli/biological-nomenclature] But as early as 1622, Gaspard Bauhin introduced in his book *Pinax theatri botanici* (English, *Illustrated exposition of plants*) containing many names of genera that were later adopted by Linnaeus.
[src:e-coli/biological-nomenclature] The introduction of two-part names (binominal nomenclature) for species by Linnaeus was a welcome simplification because as our knowledge of biodiversity expanded, so did the length of the names, many of which had become unwieldy.
[src:e-coli/biological-nomenclature] With all naturalists worldwide adopting binominal nomenclature, there arose several schools of thought about the details.
[src:e-coli/biological-nomenclature] It became ever more apparent that a detailed body of rules was necessary to govern scientific names.
[src:e-coli/biological-nomenclature] From the mid-19th century onwards, there were several initiatives to arrive at worldwide-accepted sets of rules.
[src:e-coli/biological-nomenclature] The starting point, that is the time from which these codes are in effect (usually retroactively), varies from group to group, and sometimes from rank to rank.
[src:e-coli/biological-nomenclature] In botany and mycology, the starting point is often 1 May 1753 (Linnaeus, *Species plantarum*).
[src:e-coli/biological-nomenclature] In zoology, it is 1 January 1758 (Linnaeus, *Systema Naturae*, 10th Edition).
[src:e-coli/biological-nomenclature] On the other hand, bacteriology started anew, making a clean sweep in 1980 (Skerman et al., "Approved Lists of Bacterial Names"), although maintaining the original authors and dates of publication.
[src:e-coli/biological-nomenclature] There are also differences in the way codes work.
[src:e-coli/biological-nomenclature] For example, the *ICN* (the code for algae, fungi and plants) forbids tautonyms, while the *ICZN* (the animal code) allows them.
[src:e-coli/biological-nomenclature] These codes differ in terminology, and there is a long-term project to "harmonize" this.
[src:e-coli/biological-nomenclature] For instance, the *ICN* uses "valid" in "valid publication of a name" (=the act of publishing a formal name), with "establishing a name" as the *ICZN* equivalent.
[src:e-coli/biological-nomenclature] The *ICZN* uses "valid" in "valid name" (="correct name"), with "correct name" as the *ICN* equivalent.
[src:e-coli/biological-nomenclature] Harmonization is making very limited progress.
[src:e-coli/biological-nomenclature] There are differences in respect of what kinds of types are used.
[src:e-coli/biological-nomenclature] The bacteriological code prefers living type cultures, but allows other kinds.
[src:e-coli/biological-nomenclature] There has been ongoing debate regarding which kind of type is more useful in a case like cyanobacteria.
[src:e-coli/biological-nomenclature] A more radical approach was made in 1997 when the IUBS/IUMS International Committee on Bionomenclature (ICB) presented the long debated *Draft BioCode*, proposed to replace all existing *Codes* with a harmonization of them.
[src:e-coli/biological-nomenclature] The originally planned implementation date for the BioCode draft was January 1, 2000, but agreement to replace the existing *Codes* was not reached.
[src:e-coli/biological-nomenclature] In 2011, a revised *BioCode* was proposed that, instead of replacing the existing *Codes*, would provide a unified context for them, referring to them when necessary.
[src:e-coli/biological-nomenclature] Changes in the existing codes are slowly being made in the proposed directions.
[src:e-coli/biological-nomenclature] However, participants of the last serious discussion of the draft BioCode concluded that it would probably not be implemented in their lifetimes.
[src:e-coli/biological-nomenclature] Many authors encountered problems in using the Linnean system in phylogenetic classification.
[src:e-coli/biological-nomenclature] In fact, early proponents of rank-based nomenclature, such as Alphonse de Candolle and the authors of the 1886 version of the American Ornithologists' Union code of nomenclature already envisioned that in the future, rank-based nomenclature would have to be abandoned.
[src:e-coli/biological-nomenclature] Another *Code* that was developed since 1998 is the *PhyloCode*, which now regulates names defined under phylogenetic nomenclature instead of the traditional Linnaean nomenclature.
[src:e-coli/biological-nomenclature] This new approach requires using phylogenetic definitions that refer to "specifiers", analogous to "type" under rank-based nomenclature.
[src:e-coli/biological-nomenclature] Such definitions delimit taxa under a given phylogeny, and this kind of nomenclature does not require use of absolute ranks.
[src:e-coli/biological-nomenclature] The *Code* took effect in 2020, with the publication of Phylonyms, a monograph that includes a list of the first names established under that code.
[src:e-coli/biological-nomenclature] Some protists, sometimes called **ambiregnal protists**, have been considered to be both protozoa and algae, or protozoa and fungi, and names for these have been published under either or both of the *ICZN* and the *ICN*.
[src:e-coli/biological-nomenclature] The resulting double language throughout protist classification schemes resulted in confusion.
[src:e-coli/biological-nomenclature] Slime molds, plasmodial forms and other "fungus-like" organisms claimed by both protozoologists and mycologists include mycetozoans, plasmodiophorids, acrasids, and labyrinthulomycetes.
[src:e-coli/biological-nomenclature] Fungi claimed by both protozoologists and mycologists include chytrids, blastoclads, and the gut fungi.
[src:e-coli/biological-nomenclature] Other problematic groups are the Cyanobacteria (ICNP/ICN), the Rozellida and Microsporidia (ICZN/ICN).
[src:e-coli/biological-nomenclature] The zoological code does not regulate names of taxa lower than subspecies or higher than superfamily.
[src:e-coli/biological-nomenclature] There are many attempts to introduce some order on the nomenclature of these taxa, including the PhyloCode, the Duplostensional Nomenclatural System, and circumscriptional nomenclature.
[src:e-coli/biological-nomenclature] The botanical code is applied primarily to the ranks of superfamily and below.
[src:e-coli/biological-nomenclature] There are some rules for names above the rank of superfamily, but the principle of priority does not apply to them, and the principle of typification is optional.
[src:e-coli/biological-nomenclature] These names may be either automatically typified names or be descriptive names.
[src:e-coli/biological-nomenclature] In some circumstances, a taxon has two possible names (e.g., Chrysophyceae Pascher, 1914, *nom. descrip.*; Hibberd, 1976, *nom. typificatum*).
[src:e-coli/biological-nomenclature] Descriptive names are problematic, once that, if a taxon is split, it is not obvious which new group takes the existing name.
[src:e-coli/biological-nomenclature] Meanwhile, with typified names, the existing name is taken by the new group that still bears the type of this name.
[src:e-coli/biological-nomenclature] However, typified names present special problems for microorganisms.
[src:e-coli/common-name] In biology, a **common name** is a name of a taxon or organism that is based on the normal language of everyday life.
[src:e-coli/common-name] It is often contrasted with the scientific name for the same organism, which is often based in Latin.
[src:e-coli/common-name] Common names can be used frequently, but that is not always the case.
[src:e-coli/common-name] Creating an "official" list of common names can also be an attempt to standardize the use of common names, which can sometimes vary a great deal between one part of a country and another, as well as between one country and another country, even where the same language is spoken in both places.
[src:e-coli/common-name] A common name intrinsically plays a part in a classification of objects, typically an incomplete and informal classification, in which some names are degenerate examples in that they are unique and lack reference to any other name, as is the case with say, *ginkgo*, *okapi*, and *ratel*.
[src:e-coli/common-name] The form of scientific names for organisms, called binomial nomenclature, is superficially similar to the noun-adjective form of vernacular names or common names which were used by non-modern cultures.
[src:e-coli/common-name] A collective name such as *owl* was made more precise by the addition of an adjective such as *screech*.
[src:e-coli/common-name] Linnaeus himself published a flora of his homeland Sweden, *Flora Svecica* (1745), and in this, he recorded the Swedish common names, region by region, as well as the scientific names.
[src:e-coli/common-name] The Swedish common names were all binomials (e.g. plant no.
[src:e-coli/common-name] 85 Ren-losta); the vernacular binomial system thus preceded his scientific binomial system.
[src:e-coli/common-name] The geographic range over which a particularly common name is used varies; some common names have a very local application, while others are virtually universal within a particular language.
[src:e-coli/common-name] Some such names even apply across ranges of languages; the word for *cat*, for instance, is easily recognizable in most Germanic and many Romance languages.
[src:e-coli/common-name] Many vernacular names, however, are restricted to a single country and colloquial names to local districts.
[src:e-coli/common-name] Some languages also have more than one common name for the same animal.
[src:e-coli/common-name] For example, in Irish, there are many terms that are considered outdated but still well-known for their somewhat humorous and poetic descriptions of animals.
[src:e-coli/common-name] Common names are used in the writings of both professionals and laymen.
[src:e-coli/common-name] Many examples of such common names simply are attempts to translate the scientific name into English or some other vernacular.
[src:e-coli/common-name] Such translation may be confusing in itself, or confusingly inaccurate, for example, *gratiosus* does not mean "gracile" and *gracilis* does not mean "graceful".
[src:e-coli/common-name] Various bodies and the authors of many technical and semi-technical books do not simply adapt existing common names for various organisms; they try to coin (and put into common use) comprehensive, useful, authoritative, and standardised lists of new names.
[src:e-coli/common-name] Other attempts to reconcile differences between widely separated regions, traditions, and languages, by arbitrarily imposing nomenclature, often reflect narrow perspectives and have unfortunate outcomes.
[src:e-coli/common-name] For example, members of the genus *Burhinus* occur in Australia, Southern Africa, Eurasia, and South America.
[src:e-coli/common-name] A recent trend in field manuals and bird lists is to use the name "thick-knee" for members of the genus.
[src:e-coli/common-name] This, in spite of the fact that the majority of the species occur in non-English-speaking regions and have various common names, not always English.
[src:e-coli/common-name] For example, "Dikkop" is the centuries-old South African vernacular name for their two local species: *Burhinus capensis* is the Cape dikkop (or "gewone dikkop", not to mention the presumably much older Zulu name "umBangaqhwa"); *Burhinus vermiculatus* is the "water dikkop".
[src:e-coli/common-name] The thick joints in question are not even, in fact, the birds' knees, but the intertarsal joints—in lay terms the ankles.
[src:e-coli/common-name] Furthermore, not all species in the genus have "thick knees", so the thickness of the "knees" of some species is not of clearly descriptive significance.
[src:e-coli/common-name] The family Burhinidae has members that have various common names even in English, including "stone curlews", so the choice of the name "thick-knees" is not easy to defend but is a clear illustration of the hazards of the facile coinage of terminology.
[src:e-coli/common-name] For collective nouns for various subjects, see a list of collective nouns (e.g. a flock of sheep, pack of wolves).
[src:e-coli/common-name] Some organizations have created official lists of common names, or guidelines for creating common names, hoping to standardize the use of common names.
[src:e-coli/common-name] The AFNS has been an official Australian Standard since July 2007 and has existed in draft form (The Australian Fish Names List) since 2001.
[src:e-coli/common-name] Seafood Services Australia (SSA) serve as the Secretariat for the AFNC.
[src:e-coli/common-name] The Entomological Society of America maintains a database of official common names of insects, and proposals for new entries must be submitted and reviewed by a formal committee before being added to the listing.
[src:e-coli/common-name] Efforts to standardize English names for the amphibians and reptiles of North America (north of Mexico) began in the mid-1950s.
[src:e-coli/common-name] The dynamic nature of taxonomy necessitates periodical updates and changes in the nomenclature of both scientific and common names.
[src:e-coli/common-name] The Society for the Study of Amphibians and Reptiles (SSAR) published an updated list in 1978, largely following the previous established examples, and subsequently published eight revised editions ending in 2017.
[src:e-coli/common-name] More recently the SSAR switched to an online version with a searchable database.
[src:e-coli/common-name] Standardized names for the amphibians and reptiles of Mexico in Spanish and English were first published in 1994, with a revised and updated list published in 2008.
[src:e-coli/common-name] A set of guidelines for the creation of English names for birds was published in *The Auk* in 1978.
[src:e-coli/common-name] It gave rise to *Birds of the World: Recommended English Names* and its Spanish and French companions.
[src:e-coli/common-name] The Academy of the Hebrew Language publish from time to time short dictionaries of common name in Hebrew for species that occur in Israel or surrounding countries e.g. for Reptilia in 1938, Osteichthyes in 2012, and Odonata in 2015.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] Some serotypes, such as EPEC and ETEC, are pathogenic, causing serious food poisoning in their hosts.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] Fecal–oral transmission is the major route through which pathogenic strains of the bacterium cause disease.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] This transmission method is occasionally responsible for food contamination incidents that prompt product recalls.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] Cells are able to survive outside the body for a limited amount of time, which makes them potential indicator organisms to test environmental samples for fecal contamination.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] A growing body of research, though, has examined environmentally persistent *E. coli* which can survive for many days and grow outside a host.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] The bacterium can be grown and cultured easily and inexpensively in a laboratory setting, and has been intensively investigated for over 60 years.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] *E. coli* is a chemoheterotroph whose chemically defined medium must include a source of carbon and energy.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] *E. coli* is the most widely studied prokaryotic model organism, and an important species in the fields of biotechnology and microbiology, where it has served as the host organism for the majority of work with recombinant DNA.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] Under favourable conditions, it takes as little as 20 minutes to reproduce.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] The flagella, which allow the bacteria to swim, have a peritrichous arrangement.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] The flagella attach and efface to the microvilli of the intestines via an adhesion molecule known as intimin.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] In addition, *E. coli*'s metabolism can be rewired to solely use CO2 as the source of carbon for biomass production.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] In other words, this obligate heterotroph's metabolism can be altered to display autotrophic capabilities by heterologously expressing carbon fixation genes as well as formate dehydrogenase and conducting laboratory evolution experiments.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] This may be done by using formate to reduce electron carriers and supply the ATP required in anabolic pathways inside of these synthetic autotrophs.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] When growing in the presence of a mixture of sugars, bacteria will often consume the sugars sequentially through a process known as catabolite repression.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] By repressing the expression of the genes involved in metabolizing the less preferred sugars, cells will usually first consume the sugar yielding the highest growth rate, followed by the sugar yielding the next highest growth rate, and so on.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] In doing so the cells ensure that their limited metabolic resources are being used to maximize the rate of growth.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] The well-used example of this with *E. coli* involves the growth of the bacterium on glucose and lactose, where *E. coli* will consume glucose before lactose.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] Catabolite repression has also been observed in *E. coli* in the presence of other non-glucose sugars, such as arabinose and xylose, sorbitol, rhamnose, and ribose.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] In *E. coli*, glucose catabolite repression is regulated by the phosphotransferase system, a multi-protein phosphorylation cascade that couples glucose uptake and metabolism.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] Optimum growth of *E. coli* occurs at 37 °C (99 °F), but some laboratory strains can multiply at temperatures up to 49 °C (120 °F).
[src:e-coli/e-coli] *E. coli* grows in a variety of defined laboratory media, such as lysogeny broth, or any medium that contains glucose, ammonium phosphate monobasic, sodium chloride, magnesium sulfate, potassium phosphate dibasic, and water.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] Growth can be driven by aerobic or anaerobic respiration, using a large variety of redox pairs, including the oxidation of pyruvic acid, formic acid, hydrogen, and amino acids, and the reduction of substrates such as oxygen, nitrate, fumarate, dimethyl sulfoxide, and trimethylamine N-oxide.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] *E. coli* is classified as a facultative anaerobe.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] It uses oxygen when it is present and available.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] It can, however, continue to grow in the absence of oxygen using fermentation or anaerobic respiration.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] Respiration type is managed in part by the arc system.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] The ability to continue growing in the absence of oxygen is an advantage to bacteria because their survival is increased in environments where water predominates.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] The bacterial cell cycle is divided into three stages.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] The B period occurs between the completion of cell division and the beginning of DNA replication.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] The C period encompasses the time it takes to replicate the chromosomal DNA.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] The D period refers to the stage between the conclusion of DNA replication and the end of cell division.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] The doubling rate of *E. coli* is higher when more nutrients are available.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] However, the length of the C and D periods do not change, even when the doubling time becomes less than the sum of the C and D periods.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] At the fastest growth rates, replication begins before the previous round of replication has completed, resulting in multiple replication forks along the DNA and overlapping cell cycles.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] The number of replication forks in fast growing *E. coli* typically follows 2n (n = 1, 2 or 3).
[src:e-coli/e-coli] This only happens if replication is initiated simultaneously from all origins of replications, and is referred to as synchronous replication.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] However, not all cells in a culture replicate synchronously.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] In this case cells do not have multiples of two replication forks.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] Replication initiation is then referred to being asynchronous.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] However, asynchrony can be caused by mutations to for instance *dnaA* or DnaA initiator-associating protein DiaA.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] Although *E. coli* reproduces by binary fission the two supposedly identical cells produced by cell division are functionally asymmetric with the old pole cell acting as an aging parent that repeatedly produces rejuvenated offspring.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] When exposed to an elevated stress level, damage accumulation in an old *E. coli* lineage may surpass its immortality threshold so that it arrests division and becomes mortal.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] Cellular aging is a general process, affecting prokaryotes and eukaryotes alike.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] In fact, from the more constructive point of view, the members of genus *Shigella* (*S. dysenteriae*, *S. flexneri*, *S. boydii*, and *S. sonnei*) should be classified as *E. coli* strains, a phenomenon termed taxa in disguise.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] Similarly, other strains of *E. coli* (e.g. the K-12 strain commonly used in recombinant DNA work) are sufficiently different that they would merit reclassification.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] A strain is a subgroup within the species that has unique characteristics that distinguish it from other strains.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] These differences are often detectable only at the molecular level; however, they may result in changes to the physiology or lifecycle of the bacterium.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] For example, a strain may gain pathogenic capacity, the ability to use a unique carbon source, the ability to take upon a particular ecological niche, or the ability to resist antimicrobial agents.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] Different strains of *E. coli* are often host-specific, making it possible to determine the source of fecal contamination in environmental samples.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] For example, knowing which *E. coli* strains are present in a water sample allows researchers to make assumptions about whether the contamination originated from a human, another mammal, or a bird.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] A common subdivision system of *E. coli*, but not based on evolutionary relatedness, is by serotype, which is based on major surface antigens (O antigen: part of lipopolysaccharide layer; H: flagellin; K antigen: capsule), e.g.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] It is, however, common to cite only the serogroup, i.e. the O-antigen.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] At present, about 190 serogroups are known.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] Nonpathogenic strains which are commonly used in research laboratories lack an O-antigen and are thus not serotypeable.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] Like all lifeforms, new strains of *E. coli* evolve through the natural biological processes of mutation, gene duplication, and horizontal gene transfer; in particular, 18% of the genome of the laboratory strain MG1655 was horizontally acquired since the divergence from *Salmonella*.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] *E. coli* K-12 and *E. coli* B strains are the most frequently used varieties for laboratory purposes.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] Some strains develop traits that can be harmful to a host animal.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] These virulent strains typically cause a bout of diarrhea that is often self-limiting in healthy adults but is frequently lethal to children in the developing world.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] More virulent strains, such as O157:H7, cause serious illness or death in the elderly, the very young, or the immunocompromised.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] The genera *Escherichia* and *Salmonella* diverged around 102 million years ago (credibility interval: 57–176 mya), an event unrelated to the much earlier (see *Synapsid*) divergence of their hosts: the former being found in mammals and the latter in birds and reptiles.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] This was followed by a split of an *Escherichia* ancestor into five species (*E. albertii*, *E. coli*, *E. fergusonii*, *E. hermannii*, and *E. vulneris*).
[src:e-coli/e-coli] The last *E. coli* ancestor split between 20 and 30 million years ago.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] The long-term evolution experiments using *E. coli*, begun by Richard Lenski in 1988, have allowed direct observation of genome evolution over more than 65,000 generations in the laboratory.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] For instance, *E. coli* typically do not have the ability to grow aerobically with citrate as a carbon source, which is used as a diagnostic criterion with which to differentiate *E. coli* from other, closely, related bacteria such as *Salmonella*.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] In this experiment, one population of *E. coli* unexpectedly evolved the ability to aerobically metabolize citrate, a major evolutionary shift with some hallmarks of microbial speciation.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] In the microbial world, a relationship of predation can be established similar to that observed in the animal world.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] Considered, it has been seen that *E. coli* is the prey of multiple generalist predators, such as *Myxococcus xanthus*.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] In this predator-prey relationship, a parallel evolution of both species is observed through genomic and phenotypic modifications.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] However, in most studies, either O157:H7, K-12 MG1655, or K-12 W3110 were used as a representative *E. coli*.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] The genome of the type strain has only lately (2013) been sequenced.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] Many strains belonging to this species have been isolated and characterised.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] In addition to serotype (*vide supra*), they can be classified according to their phylogeny, i.e. the inferred evolutionary history, as shown below where the species is divided into six groups as of 2014.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] Particularly the use of whole genome sequences yields highly supported phylogenies.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] The phylogroup structure remains robust to newer methods and sequences, which sometimes adds newer groups, giving 8 or 14 as of 2023.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] The link between phylogenetic distance ("relatedness") and pathology is small, *e.g.* the O157:H7 serotype strains, which form a clade ("an exclusive group")—group E below—are all enterohaemorragic strains (EHEC), but not all EHEC strains are closely related.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] In fact, four different species of *Shigella* are nested among *E. coli* strains (*vide supra*), while *E. albertii* and *E. fergusonii* are outside this group.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] Indeed, all *Shigella* species were placed within a single subspecies of *E. coli* in a phylogenomic study that included the type strain.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] All commonly used research strains of *E. coli* belong to group A and are derived mainly from Clifton's K-12 strain (λ+ F+; O16) and to a lesser degree from d'Herelle's "Bacillus coli" strain (B strain; O7).
[src:e-coli/e-coli] There have been multiple proposals to revise the taxonomy to match phylogeny.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] However, all these proposals need to face the fact that *Shigella* remains a widely used name in medicine and find ways to reduce any confusion that can stem from renaming.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] The first complete DNA sequence of an *E. coli* genome (laboratory strain K-12 derivative MG1655) was published in 1997.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] It is a circular DNA molecule 4.6 million base pairs in length, containing 4288 annotated protein-coding genes (organized into 2584 operons), seven ribosomal RNA (rRNA) operons, and 86 transfer RNA (tRNA) genes.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] Despite having been the subject of intensive genetic analysis for about 40 years, many of these genes were previously unknown.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] The coding density was found to be very high, with a mean distance between genes of only 118 base pairs.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] The genome was observed to contain a significant number of transposable genetic elements, repeat elements, cryptic prophages, and bacteriophage remnants.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] More than three hundred complete genomic sequences of *Escherichia* and *Shigella* species are known.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] The genome sequence of the type strain of *E. coli* was added to this collection before 2014.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] Comparison of these sequences shows a remarkable amount of diversity; only about 20% of each genome represents sequences present in every one of the isolates, while around 80% of each genome can vary among isolates.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] Each individual genome contains between 4,000 and 5,500 genes, but the total number of different genes among all of the sequenced *E. coli* strains (the pangenome) exceeds 16,000.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] This very large variety of component genes has been interpreted to mean that two-thirds of the *E. coli* pangenome originated in other species and arrived through the process of horizontal gene transfer.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] Genes in *E. coli* are usually named in accordance with the uniform nomenclature proposed by Demerec et al.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] Gene names are 3-letter acronyms that derive from their function (when known) or mutant phenotype and are italicized.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] When multiple genes have the same acronym, the different genes are designated by a capital later that follows the acronym and is also italicized.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] For instance, *recA* is named after its role in homologous recombination plus the letter A.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] Functionally related genes are named *recB*, *recC*, *recD* etc.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] The proteins are named by uppercase acronyms, e.g.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] When the genome of *E. coli* strain K-12 substr.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] MG1655 was sequenced, all known or predicted protein-coding genes were numbered (more or less) in their order on the genome and abbreviated by b numbers, such as b2819 (= *recD*).
[src:e-coli/e-coli] The "b" names were created after Fred Blattner, who led the genome sequence effort.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] Another numbering system was introduced with the sequence of another *E. coli* K-12 substrain, W3110, which was sequenced in Japan and hence uses numbers starting by JW...
[src:e-coli/e-coli] Note, however, that most databases have their own numbering system, e.g. the EcoGene database uses EG10826 for *recD*.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] Finally, ECK numbers are specifically used for alleles in the MG1655 strain of *E. coli* K-12.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] Complete lists of genes and their synonyms can be obtained from databases such as EcoGene or Uniprot.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] The genome sequence of *E. coli* predicts 4288 protein-coding genes, of which 38 percent initially had no attributed function.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] Comparison with five other sequenced microbes reveals ubiquitous as well as narrowly distributed gene families; many families of similar genes within *E. coli* are also evident.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] The largest family of paralogous proteins contains 80 ABC transporters.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] The genome as a whole is strikingly organized with respect to the local direction of replication; guanines, oligonucleotides possibly related to replication and recombination, and most genes are so oriented.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] The genome also contains insertion sequence (IS) elements, phage remnants, and many other patches of unusual composition indicating genome plasticity through horizontal transfer.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] Several studies have experimentally investigated the proteome of *E. coli*.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] By 2006, 1,627 (38%) of the predicted proteins (open reading frames, ORFs) had been identified experimentally.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] 2020 detected 2,586 proteins with at least 2 peptides (60% of all proteins).
[src:e-coli/e-coli] Although much fewer bacterial proteins seem to have post-translational modifications (PTMs) compared to eukaryotic proteins, a substantial number of proteins are modified in *E. coli*.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] (2018) found 227 phosphoproteins of which 173 were phosphorylated on histidine.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] The majority of phosphorylated amino acids were serine (1,220 sites) with only 246 sites on histidine and 501 phosphorylated threonines and 162 tyrosines.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] The interactome of *E. coli* has been studied by affinity purification and mass spectrometry (AP/MS) and by analyzing the binary interactions among its proteins.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] Due to the low cost and speed with which it can be grown and modified in laboratory settings, *E. coli* is a popular expression platform for the production of recombinant proteins used in therapeutics.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] One advantage to using *E. coli* over another expression platform is that *E. coli* naturally does not export many proteins into the periplasm, making it easier to recover a protein of interest without cross-contamination.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] The *E. coli* K-12 strains and their derivatives (DH1, DH5α, MG1655, RV308 and W3110) are the strains most widely used by the biotechnology industry.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] Nonpathogenic *E. coli* strain Nissle 1917 (EcN), (Mutaflor) and *E. coli* O83:K24:H31 (Colinfant)) are used as probiotic agents in medicine, mainly for the treatment of various gastrointestinal diseases, including inflammatory bowel disease.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] It is thought that the EcN strain might impede the growth of opportunistic pathogens, including *Salmonella* and other coliform enteropathogens, through the production of microcin proteins the production of siderophores.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] Most *E. coli* strains do not cause disease, naturally living in the gut, but virulent strains can cause gastroenteritis, urinary tract infections, neonatal meningitis, hemorrhagic colitis, and Crohn's disease.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] Common signs and symptoms include severe abdominal cramps, diarrhea, hemorrhagic colitis, vomiting, and sometimes fever.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] In rarer cases, virulent strains are also responsible for bowel necrosis (tissue death) and perforation without progressing to hemolytic–uremic syndrome, peritonitis, mastitis, sepsis, and gram-negative pneumonia.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] Very young children are more susceptible to develop severe illness, such as hemolytic uremic syndrome; however, healthy individuals of all ages are at risk to the severe consequences that may arise as a result of being infected with *E. coli*.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] Some strains of *E. coli*, for example O157:H7, can produce Shiga toxin.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] The Shiga toxin causes inflammatory responses in target cells of the gut, leaving behind lesions which result in the bloody diarrhea that is a symptom of a Shiga toxin-producing *E. coli* (STEC) infection.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] This toxin further causes premature destruction of the red blood cells, which then clog the body's filtering system, the kidneys, in some rare cases (usually in children and the elderly) causing hemolytic-uremic syndrome (HUS), which may lead to kidney failure and even death.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] Signs of hemolytic uremic syndrome include decreased frequency of urination, lethargy, and paleness of cheeks and inside the lower eyelids.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] In 25% of HUS patients, complications of the nervous system occur, which in turn causes strokes.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] In addition, this strain causes the buildup of fluid (since the kidneys do not work), leading to edema around the lungs, legs, and arms.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] This increase in fluid buildup, especially around the lungs, impedes the functioning of the heart, causing an increase in blood pressure.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] Uropathogenic *E. coli* (UPEC) is one of the main causes of urinary tract infections.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] It is part of the normal microbiota in the gut and can be introduced in many ways.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] In particular for females, the direction of wiping after defecation (wiping back to front) can lead to fecal contamination of the urogenital orifices.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] Anal intercourse can also introduce this bacterium into the male urethra, and in switching from anal to vaginal intercourse, the male can also introduce UPEC to the female urogenital system.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] Enterotoxigenic *E. coli* (ETEC) is the most common cause of traveler's diarrhea, with as many as 840 million cases worldwide in developing countries each year.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] The bacteria, typically transmitted through contaminated food or drinking water, adheres to the intestinal lining, where it secretes either of two types of enterotoxins, leading to watery diarrhea.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] The rate and severity of infections are higher among children under the age of five, including as many as 380,000 deaths annually.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] In May 2011, one *E. coli* strain, O104:H4, was the subject of a bacterial outbreak that began in Germany.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] Certain strains of *E. coli* are a major cause of foodborne illness.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] The outbreak started when several people in Germany were infected with enterohemorrhagic *E. coli* (EHEC) bacteria, leading to hemolytic-uremic syndrome (HUS), a medical emergency that requires urgent treatment.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] The outbreak spread to 15 other countries, including regions in North America.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] On 30 June 2011, the German *Bundesinstitut für Risikobewertung (BfR)* (Federal Institute for Risk Assessment, a federal institute within the German Federal Ministry of Food, Agriculture and Consumer Protection) announced that seeds of fenugreek from Egypt were likely the cause of the EHEC outbreak.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] Some studies have demonstrated an absence of *E. coli* in the gut flora of subjects with the metabolic disorder Phenylketonuria.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] It is hypothesized that the absence of these normal bacteria impairs the production of the key vitamins B2 (riboflavin) and K2 (menaquinone) – vitamins which are implicated in many physiological roles in humans such as cellular and bone metabolism – and so contributes to the disorder.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] The time between ingesting the STEC bacteria and feeling sick is called the "incubation period".
[src:e-coli/e-coli] The incubation period is usually 3–4 days after the exposure, but may be as short as 1 day or as long as 10 days.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] The symptoms often begin slowly with mild belly pain or non-bloody diarrhea that worsens over several days.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] HUS, if it occurs, develops an average 7 days after the first symptoms, when the diarrhea is improving.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] Diagnosis of infectious diarrhea and identification of antimicrobial resistance is performed using a stool culture with subsequent antibiotic sensitivity testing.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] It requires a minimum of 2 days and maximum of several weeks to culture gastrointestinal pathogens.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] The sensitivity (true positive) and specificity (true negative) rates for stool culture vary by pathogen, although a number of human pathogens can not be cultured.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] For culture-positive samples, antimicrobial resistance testing takes an additional 12–24 hours to perform.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] Current point of care molecular diagnostic tests can identify *E. coli* and antimicrobial resistance in the identified strains much faster than culture and sensitivity testing.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] Microarray-based platforms can identify specific pathogenic strains of *E. coli* and *E. coli*-specific AMR genes in two hours or less with high sensitivity and specificity, but the size of the test panel (i.e., total pathogens and antimicrobial resistance genes) is limited.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] Newer metagenomics-based infectious disease diagnostic platforms are currently being developed to overcome the various limitations of culture and all currently available molecular diagnostic technologies.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] The mainstay of treatment is the assessment of dehydration and replacement of fluid and electrolytes.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] The antibiotic used depends upon susceptibility patterns in the particular geographical region.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] Currently, the antibiotics of choice are fluoroquinolones or azithromycin, with an emerging role for rifaximin.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] Rifaximin, a semisynthetic rifamycin derivative, is an effective and well-tolerated antibacterial for the management of adults with non-invasive traveller's diarrhea.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] Rifaximin was significantly more effective than placebo and no less effective than ciprofloxacin in reducing the duration of diarrhea.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] While rifaximin is effective in patients with *E. coli*-predominant traveller's diarrhea, it appears ineffective in patients infected with inflammatory or invasive enteropathogens.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] ETEC is the type of *E. coli* that most vaccine development efforts are focused on.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] Antibodies against the LT and major CFs of ETEC provide protection against LT-producing, ETEC-expressing homologous CFs.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] Oral inactivated vaccines consisting of toxin antigen and whole cells, i.e. the licensed recombinant cholera B subunit (rCTB)-WC cholera vaccine Dukoral, have been developed.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] There are currently no licensed vaccines for ETEC, though several are in various stages of development.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] In different trials, the rCTB-WC cholera vaccine provided high (85–100%) short-term protection.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] An oral ETEC vaccine candidate consisting of rCTB and formalin inactivated *E. coli* bacteria expressing major CFs has been shown in clinical trials to be safe, immunogenic, and effective against severe diarrhoea in American travelers but not against ETEC diarrhoea in young children in Egypt.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] A modified ETEC vaccine consisting of recombinant *E. coli* strains over-expressing the major CFs and a more LT-like hybrid toxoid called LCTBA, are undergoing clinical testing.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] Other proven prevention methods for *E. coli* transmission include handwashing and improved sanitation and drinking water, as transmission occurs through fecal contamination of food and water supplies.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] Additionally, thoroughly cooking meat and avoiding consumption of raw, unpasteurized beverages, such as juices and milk are other proven methods for preventing *E. coli*.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] Lastly, cross-contamination of utensils and work spaces should be avoided when preparing food.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] Because of its long history of laboratory culture and ease of manipulation, *E. coli* plays an important role in modern biological engineering and industrial microbiology.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] The work of Stanley Norman Cohen and Herbert Boyer in *E. coli*, using plasmids and restriction enzymes to create recombinant DNA, became a foundation of biotechnology.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] Many proteins previously thought difficult or impossible to be expressed in *E. coli* in folded form have been successfully expressed in *E. coli*.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] Modified *E. coli* cells have been used in vaccine development, bioremediation, production of biofuels, lighting, and production of immobilised enzymes.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] Strain K-12 is a mutant form of *E. coli* that over-expresses the enzyme Alkaline phosphatase (ALP).
[src:e-coli/e-coli] The mutation arises due to a defect in the gene that constantly codes for the enzyme.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] A gene that is producing a product without any inhibition is said to have constitutive activity.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] This particular mutant form is used to isolate and purify the aforementioned enzyme.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] Strain OP50 of *Escherichia coli* is used for maintenance of *Caenorhabditis elegans* cultures.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] Strain JM109 is a mutant form of *E. coli* that is recA and endA deficient.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] The strain can be utilized for blue/white screening when the cells carry the fertility factor episome.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] Lack of recA decreases the possibility of unwanted restriction of the DNA of interest and lack of endA inhibit plasmid DNA decomposition.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] Thus, JM109 is useful for cloning and expression systems.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] In 1946, Joshua Lederberg and Edward Tatum first described the phenomenon known as bacterial conjugation using *E. coli* as a model bacterium, and it remains the primary model to study conjugation.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] *E. coli* was an integral part of the first experiments to understand phage genetics, and early researchers, such as Seymour Benzer, used *E. coli* and phage T4 to understand the topography of gene structure.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] Prior to Benzer's research, it was not known whether the gene was a linear structure, or if it had a branching pattern.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] Biochemistry and replication machinery were not altered.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] By evaluating the possible combination of nanotechnologies with landscape ecology, complex habitat landscapes can be generated with details at the nanoscale.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] On such synthetic ecosystems, evolutionary experiments with *E. coli* have been performed to study the spatial biophysics of adaptation in an island biogeography on-chip.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] In other studies, non-pathogenic *E. coli* has been used as a model microorganism towards understanding the effects of simulated microgravity (on Earth) on the same.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] Since 1961, scientists proposed the idea of genetic circuits used for computational tasks.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] Collaboration between biologists and computing scientists has allowed designing digital logic gates on the metabolism of *E. coli*.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] As Lac operon is a two-stage process, genetic regulation in the bacteria is used to realize computing functions.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] The process is controlled at the transcription stage of DNA into messenger RNA.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] Studies are being performed attempting to program *E. coli* to solve complicated mathematics problems, such as the Hamiltonian path problem.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] A computer to control protein production of *E. coli* within yeast cells has been developed.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] A method has also been developed to use bacteria to behave as an LCD screen.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] In July 2017, separate experiments with *E. coli* published on Nature showed the potential of using living cells for computing tasks and storing information.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] A team formed with collaborators of the Biodesign Institute at Arizona State University and Harvard's Wyss Institute for Biologically Inspired Engineering developed a biological computer inside *E. coli* that responded to a dozen inputs.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] The team called the computer "ribocomputer", as it was composed of ribonucleic acid.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] Meanwhile, Harvard researchers probed that is possible to store information in bacteria after successfully archiving images and movies in the DNA of living *E. coli* cells.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] In 2021, a team led by biophysicist Sangram Bagh realized a study with *E. coli* to solve 2 × 2 maze problems to probe the principle for distributed computing among cells.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] In 1885, the German-Austrian pediatrician Theodor Escherich discovered this organism in the feces of healthy individuals.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] He called it *Bacterium coli commune* because it is found in the colon.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] Early classifications of prokaryotes placed these in a handful of genera based on their shape and motility (at that time Ernst Haeckel's classification of bacteria in the kingdom Monera was in place).
[src:e-coli/e-coli] In 1996, an outbreak of *E. coli* food poisoning occurred in Wishaw, Scotland, killing 21 people.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] This death toll was exceeded in 2011, when an *E. coli* O104:H4 outbreak starting in Germany, linked to organic fenugreek sprouts, killed 53 people.
[src:e-coli/e-coli] In 2024, an outbreak of *E. coli* food poisoning occurred across the U.S. was linked to U.S.-grown organic carrots causing one fatality and dozens of illnesses.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Humans have a large and highly developed prefrontal cortex, the region of the brain associated with higher cognition.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] They are intelligent beings, capable of episodic memory, flexible facial expressions, self-awareness and a theory of mind.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] The human mind is capable of introspection (meta-cognition), private thought, imagination, volition and forming views on existence.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Humans can also mentally travel through time (chronesthesia) which signifies episodic foresight.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] These attributes have allowed great technological advancements through reason and the transmission of knowledge to future generations.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] In cultural anthropology, the cumulative preservation and advancement of knowledge across generations is known as the ratchet effect.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Humans are omnivorous, capable of consuming a wide variety of plant and animal material, and have used fire to prepare and cook food.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] They can survive for up to eight weeks without food, and three or four days without water.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Humans are generally diurnal, sleeping on average seven to nine hours per day.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Childbirth is dangerous, with a high risk of complications and death.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Both the mother and the father typically provide care for human offspring, who are helpless at birth.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Genes and the environment influence human biological variation in appearance, physiology, immune system, mental abilities, body size and lifespan.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Though humans vary in many traits, any two humans are on average over 99% genetically similar, with the most genetically diverse populations from Africa.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] The greatest degree of genetic variation exists between males and females.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] On average, males have greater body strength and females generally have a higher body fat percentage.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Females undergo menopause and become infertile potentially decades before the end of their lives.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] They also have a longer life span in almost every population around the world.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] The division into male and female gender roles has varied historically, and challenges to predominant gender norms have recurred in many societies.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Humans evolved from other hominins in Africa several million years ago.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Although some scientists equate humans with all members of the genus *Homo*, in common usage it generally refers to *Homo sapiens*, the only extant member.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] *Homo sapiens* emerged around 300,000 years ago and migrated out of Africa, gradually replacing local populations of archaic humans.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Early humans were hunter-gatherers, before the invention of agriculture and domestication of animals led to permanent settlement in the Fertile Crescent and other cradles of civilization.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] As food surpluses enabled populations to become larger and denser, forms of governance developed, the use of writing became necessary, and a number of civilizations rose and fell.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Humans have continued to expand, with over 8.3 billion humans occupying almost all regions of Earth in 2026.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Moreover, humans have visited the Moon and explored other celestial bodies using unmanned spacecraft, becoming the first known species to do so.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] All modern humans are classified into the species *Homo sapiens*, coined by Carl Linnaeus in his 1735 work *Systema Naturae*.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] The generic name *Homo* is a learned 18th-century derivation from Latin *homō*, which refers to humans of either sex.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] The word *human* can refer to all members of the *Homo* genus.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] The name *Homo sapiens* means 'wise man' or 'knowledgeable man'.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] There is disagreement if certain extinct members of the genus, namely Neanderthals, should be included as a separate species of humans or as a subspecies of *H. sapiens*.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Although the word *animal* is colloquially used as an antonym for *human*, and contrary to a common biological misconception, humans are animals.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Humans belong to the biological family of apes (superfamily Hominoidea).
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] The lineage of apes that eventually gave rise to humans first split from gibbons (family Hylobatidae), next orangutans (genus *Pongo*), then gorillas (genus *Gorilla*), and finally, chimpanzees and bonobos (genus *Pan*).
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] The last split, between the human and chimpanzee–bonobo lineages, took place around 8–4 million years ago, in the late Miocene epoch.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] During this split, chromosome 2 was formed from the joining of two other chromosomes, leaving humans with only 23 pairs of chromosomes, compared to 24 for the other apes.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Following their split with chimpanzees and bonobos, the hominins diversified into many species and at least two distinct genera.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] All but one of these lineages – representing the genus *Homo* and its sole extant species *Homo sapiens* – are now extinct.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] The genus *Homo* evolved from *Australopithecus*.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Though fossils from the transition are scarce, the earliest members of *Homo* share several key traits with *Australopithecus*.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Due to the scant available evidence, the time of the divergence to the genus *Homo* does not have a consensus.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Some studies using molecular clock techniques estimate the *Homo* genus appeared 4.30–2.56 million years ago, while others contest that some early *Homo* species are incorrectly included in the genus and therefore put this estimate at about 1.87 million years ago.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] The earliest record of *Homo* is the 2.8 million-year-old specimen LD 350-1 from Ethiopia, and the earliest named species are *Homo habilis* and *Homo rudolfensis* which evolved by 2.3 million years ago.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] *H. erectus* (the African variant is sometimes called *H. ergaster*) evolved 2 million years ago and was the first archaic human species to leave Africa and disperse across Eurasia.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] *H. erectus* also was the first to evolve a characteristically human body plan.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] *Homo sapiens* emerged in Africa at least 300,000 years ago from a species commonly designated as either *H. heidelbergensis* or *H. rhodesiensis*, the descendants of *H. erectus* that remained in Africa.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] *H. sapiens* migrated out of the continent, gradually replacing or interbreeding with local populations of archaic humans.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Humans began exhibiting behavioral modernity about 160,000–70,000 years ago, and possibly earlier.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] This development was likely selected amidst natural climate change in Middle to Late Pleistocene Africa.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] The "out of Africa" migration took place in at least two waves, the first around 130,000 to 100,000 years ago, the second (Southern Dispersal) around 70,000 to 50,000 years ago.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Human evolution was not a simple linear or branched progression but involved interbreeding between related species.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Genomic research has shown that hybridization between substantially diverged lineages was common in human evolution.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] DNA evidence suggests that several genes of Neanderthal origin are present among all non sub-Saharan-African populations, and Neanderthals and other hominins, such as Denisovans, may have contributed up to 6% of their genome to present-day non sub-Saharan-African humans.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Human evolution is characterized by a number of morphological, developmental, physiological, and behavioral changes that have taken place since the split between the last common ancestor of humans and chimpanzees.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] The most significant of these adaptations are hairlessness, obligate bipedalism, increased brain size and decreased sexual dimorphism (neoteny).
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] The relationship between all these changes is the subject of ongoing debate.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Until about 12,000 years ago, all humans lived as hunter-gatherers.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] The Neolithic Revolution (the invention of agriculture) first took place in Southwest Asia and spread through large parts of the Old World over the following millennia.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] It also occurred independently in Mesoamerica (about 6,000 years ago), China, Papua New Guinea, and the Sahel and West Savanna regions of Africa.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] The formation of permanent human settlements, the domestication of animals and the use of metal tools was followed by permanent food surplus, for the first time in history.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Agriculture and sedentary lifestyle led to the emergence of early civilizations.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] An urban revolution took place in the 4th millennium BCE with the development of city-states, particularly Sumerian cities located in Mesopotamia.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] It was in these cities that the earliest known form of writing, cuneiform script, appeared around 3000 BCE.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Other major civilizations to develop around this time were Ancient Egypt and the Indus Valley Civilization.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] They eventually traded with each other and invented technology such as wheels, plows and sails.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Emerging by 3000 BCE, the Caral–Supe civilization is the oldest complex civilization in the Americas.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Astronomy and mathematics were also developed and the Great Pyramid of Giza was built.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] There is evidence of a severe drought lasting about a hundred years that may have caused the decline of these civilizations, with new ones appearing in the aftermath.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Babylonians came to dominate Mesopotamia while others, such as the Poverty Point culture, Minoans and the Shang dynasty, rose to prominence in new areas.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] The Late Bronze Age collapse around 1200 BCE resulted in the disappearance of a number of civilizations and the beginning of the Greek Dark Ages.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] During this period iron started replacing bronze, leading to the Iron Age.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] In the 5th century BCE, history started being recorded as a discipline, which provided a much clearer picture of life at the time.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Between the 8th and 6th century BCE, Europe entered the classical antiquity age, a period when ancient Greece and ancient Rome flourished.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Around this time other civilizations also came to prominence.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] The Maya civilization started to build cities and create complex calendars.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] In Africa, the Kingdom of Aksum overtook the declining Kingdom of Kush and facilitated trade between India and the Mediterranean.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] In West Asia, the Achaemenid Empire's system of centralized governance became the precursor to many later empires, while the Gupta Empire in India and the Han dynasty in China have been described as golden ages in their respective regions.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Following the fall of the Western Roman Empire in 476, Europe entered the Middle Ages.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] During this period, Christianity and the Church would act as a source of authority and education.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] In the Middle East, Islam became the prominent religion and expanded into North Africa.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] It led to an Islamic Golden Age, inspiring achievements in architecture, the revival of old advances in science and technology, and the formation of a distinct way of life.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] The Christian and Islamic worlds would eventually clash, with the Kingdom of England, the Kingdom of France and the Holy Roman Empire declaring a series of holy wars to regain control of the Holy Land from Muslims.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] In the Americas, between 200 and 900 CE Mesoamerica was in its Classic Period, while further north, complex Mississippian societies would arise starting around 800 CE.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] The Mongol Empire would conquer much of Eurasia in the 13th and 14th centuries.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Over this same time period, the Mali Empire in Africa grew to be the largest empire on the continent, stretching from Senegambia to Ivory Coast.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Oceania would see the rise of the Tuʻi Tonga Empire which expanded across many islands in the South Pacific.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] By the late 15th century, the Aztecs and Inca had become the dominant power in Mesoamerica and the Andes, respectively.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] The early modern period in Europe and the Near East (c.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] 1450–1800) began with the final defeat of the Byzantine Empire, and the rise of the Ottoman Empire.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Meanwhile, Japan entered the Edo period, the Qing dynasty rose in China and the Mughal Empire ruled much of India.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Europe underwent the Renaissance, starting in the 15th century, and the Age of Discovery began with the exploring and colonizing of new regions.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] This included the colonization of the Americas and the Columbian Exchange.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] This expansion led to the Atlantic slave trade and the genocide of the Americas' indigenous peoples.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] This period also marked the Scientific Revolution, with great advances in mathematics, mechanics, astronomy and physiology.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] The late modern period (1800–present) saw the Industrial and Technological Revolution bring such discoveries as imaging technology, major innovations in transport, and energy development.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Influenced by Enlightenment ideals, the Americas and Europe experienced a period of political revolutions known as the Age of Revolution.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] The Napoleonic Wars raged through Europe in the early 1800s, Spain lost most of its colonies in the New World, while Europeans continued expansion into Africa – where European control went from 10% to almost 90% in less than 50 years – and Oceania.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] In the 19th century, the British Empire expanded to become the world's largest empire.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] A tenuous balance of power among European nations collapsed in 1914 with the outbreak of the First World War, one of the deadliest conflicts in history.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] In the 1930s, a worldwide economic crisis led to the rise of authoritarian regimes and a Second World War, involving almost all of the world's countries.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] The war's destruction led to the collapse of most global empires, leading to widespread decolonization.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Following the conclusion of the Second World War in 1945, the United States and the Soviet Union emerged as the remaining global superpowers.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] This led to a Cold War that saw a struggle for global influence, including a nuclear arms race and a space race, ending in the collapse of the Soviet Union.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] The current Information Age, spurred by the development of the Internet and artificial intelligence systems, sees the world becoming increasingly globalized and interconnected.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Early human settlements were dependent on proximity to water and – depending on the lifestyle – other natural resources used for subsistence, such as populations of animal prey for hunting and arable land for growing crops and grazing livestock.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Modern humans, however, have a great capacity for altering their habitats by means of technology, irrigation, urban planning, construction, deforestation and desertification.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Human settlements continue to be vulnerable to natural disasters, especially those placed in hazardous locations and with low quality of construction.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Grouping and deliberate habitat alteration is often done with the goals of providing protection, accumulating comforts or material wealth, expanding the available food, improving aesthetics, increasing knowledge or enhancing the exchange of resources.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Humans are one of the most adaptable species, despite having a low or narrow tolerance for many of the Earth's extreme environments.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Currently the species is present in all eight biogeographical realms, although their presence in the Antarctic realm is limited to research stations and annually there is a population decline in the winter months of this realm.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Humans have had a dramatic effect on the environment.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Human population growth, industrialization, land development, overconsumption and combustion of fossil fuels have led to environmental destruction and pollution that significantly contributes to the ongoing mass extinction of other forms of life.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Within the last century, humans have also explored the deep sea and outer space.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Human habitation within these hostile environments is restrictive and expensive, typically limited in duration, and restricted to scientific, military, or industrial expeditions.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Humans have visited the Moon and made their presence known on other celestial bodies through human-made robotic spacecraft.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Since 2000, there has been continuous human presence in space through habitation on the International Space Station.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] By using advanced tools and clothing, humans have been able to extend their tolerance to a wide variety of temperatures, humidities, and altitudes.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] As a result, humans are a cosmopolitan species found in almost all regions of the world, including tropical rainforest, arid desert, extremely cold arctic regions, and heavily polluted cities; in comparison, most other species are confined to a few geographical areas by their limited adaptability.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] The human population is not, however, uniformly distributed on the Earth's surface, because the population density varies from one region to another, and large stretches of surface are almost completely uninhabited, like Antarctica and vast swathes of the ocean.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Most humans (61%) live in Asia; the remainder live in the Americas (14%), Africa (14%), Europe (11%), and Oceania (0.5%).
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Estimates of the population at the time agriculture emerged in around 10,000 BC have ranged between 1 million and 15 million.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Around 50–60 million people lived in the combined eastern and western Roman Empire in the 4th century AD.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Bubonic plagues, first recorded in the 6th century AD, reduced the population by 50%, with the Black Death killing 75–200 million people in Eurasia and North Africa alone.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Human population is believed to have reached one billion in 1800.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] It has since then increased exponentially, reaching two billion in 1930 and three billion in 1960, four in 1975, five in 1987 and six billion in 1999.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] It passed seven billion in 2011 and passed eight billion in 2022.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] It took over two million years of human prehistory and history for the human population to reach one billion and only 207 years more to grow to 7 billion.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] The combined biomass of the carbon of all the humans on Earth in 2018 was estimated at 60 million tons, about 10 times larger than that of all non-domesticated mammals.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] In 2018, 4.2 billion humans (55%) lived in urban areas, up from 751 million in 1950.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] The most urbanized regions are Northern America (82%), Latin America (81%), Europe (74%) and Oceania (68%), with Africa and Asia having nearly 90% of the world's 3.4 billion rural population.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Problems for humans living in cities include various forms of pollution and crime, especially in inner city and suburban slums.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Most aspects of human physiology are closely homologous to corresponding aspects of animal physiology.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] The dental formula of humans is: 2.1.2.32.1.2.3, like other catarrhines.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Humans have proportionately shorter palates and much smaller teeth than other primates.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] They are the only primates to have short, relatively flush canine teeth.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Humans have characteristically crowded teeth, with gaps from lost teeth usually closing up quickly in young individuals.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Humans are gradually losing their third molars, with some individuals having them congenitally absent.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Humans share with chimpanzees a vestigial tail, appendix, flexible shoulder joints, grasping fingers and opposable thumbs.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Humans also have a more barrel-shaped chest in contrast to the funnel shape of other apes, an adaptation for bipedal respiration.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Apart from bipedalism and brain size, humans differ from chimpanzees mostly in smelling, hearing and digesting proteins.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] While humans have a density of hair follicles comparable to other apes, it is predominantly vellus hair, most of which is so short and wispy as to be practically invisible.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Humans have about 2 million sweat glands spread over their entire bodies, many more than chimpanzees, whose sweat glands are scarce and are mainly located on the palm of the hand and on the soles of the feet.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] It is estimated that the worldwide average height for an adult human male is about 171 cm (5 ft 7 in), while the worldwide average height for adult human females is about 159 cm (5 ft 3 in).
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Shrinkage of stature may begin in middle age in some individuals but tends to be typical in the extremely aged.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Throughout history, human populations have universally become taller, probably as a consequence of better nutrition, healthcare, and living conditions.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] The average mass of an adult human is 59 kg (130 lb) for females and 77 kg (170 lb) for males.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Like many other conditions, body weight and body type are influenced by both genetic susceptibility and environment and varies greatly among individuals.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Humans have a far faster and more accurate throw than other animals.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Humans are also among the best long-distance runners in the animal kingdom, but slower over short distances.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Humans' thinner body hair and more productive sweat glands help avoid heat exhaustion while running for long distances.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Compared to other apes, the human heart produces greater stroke volume and cardiac output and the aorta is proportionately larger.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Humans are, like all animals, plants, and fungi, a eukaryotic, and like most animals a diploid species.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Each somatic cell has two sets of 23 chromosomes, each set received from one parent; gametes have only one set of chromosomes, which is a mixture of the two parental sets.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Among the 23 pairs of chromosomes, there are 22 pairs of autosomes and one pair of sex chromosomes.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] In humans, sex determination is primarily mediated by the SRY gene located on the Y chromosome.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] While the typical configuration follows an XY sex-determination system (XX for females, XY for males), the genetic expression of the Sex-determining Region Y protein is the critical factor in initiating male gonadal differentiation.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Consequently, individuals may be born with a chromosomal genotype that does not align with their phenotypic sex, a condition often resulting in infertility due to the absence of specific genes required for gametogenesis.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Genes and environment influence human biological variation in visible characteristics, physiology, disease susceptibility and mental abilities.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] The exact influence of genes and environment on certain traits is not well understood.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] While no humans – not even monozygotic twins – are genetically identical, two humans on average will have a genetic similarity of 99.5%-99.9%.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] This makes them more homogeneous than other great apes, including chimpanzees.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] This small variation in human DNA compared to many other species suggests a population bottleneck during the Late Pleistocene (around 100,000 years ago), in which the human population was reduced to a small number of breeding pairs.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] The forces of natural selection have continued to operate on human populations, with evidence that certain regions of the genome display directional selection in the past 15,000 years.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] In 1984, the US government began to plan the human genome project (HGP), which officially started in 1990.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Utilizing the data from the HGP, 92% of the human genome was first sequenced in 2001.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] After the HGP was completed in April 2003, the All of Us Research Program in 2022 released its first major dataset which included nearly 100,000 whole genome sequences.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] By April 2023, approximately 245,000 genomes had been sequenced.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] In 2012 the International HapMap Project had compared the genomes of 1,184 individuals from 11 populations and identified 1.6 million single nucleotide polymorphisms.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] African populations harbor the highest number of private genetic variants.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] While many of the common variants found in populations outside of Africa are also found on the African continent, there are still large numbers that are private to these regions, especially Oceania and the Americas.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] By 2010 estimates, humans have approximately 22,000 genes.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] By comparing mitochondrial DNA, which is inherited only from the mother, geneticists have concluded that the last female common ancestor whose genetic marker is found in all modern humans, the so-called mitochondrial Eve, must have lived around 90,000 to 200,000 years ago.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Most human reproduction takes place by internal fertilization via sexual intercourse, but can also occur through assisted reproductive technology procedures.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] The average gestation period is 38 weeks, but a normal pregnancy can vary by up to 37 days.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Embryonic development in the human covers the first eight weeks of development; at the beginning of the ninth week the embryo is termed a fetus.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Humans are able to induce early labor or perform a caesarean section if the child needs to be born earlier for medical reasons.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] In developed countries, infants are typically 3–4 kg (7–9 lb) in weight and 47–53 cm (19–21 in) in height at birth.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] However, low birth weight is common in developing countries, and contributes to the high levels of infant mortality in these regions.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Compared with other species, human childbirth is dangerous, with a much higher risk of complications and death.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] The size of the fetus's head is more closely matched to the pelvis than in other primates.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] The reason for this is not completely understood, but it contributes to a painful labor that can last 24 hours or more.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] The chances of a successful labor increased significantly during the 20th century in wealthier countries with the advent of new medical technologies.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] In contrast, pregnancy and natural childbirth remain hazardous ordeals in developing regions of the world, with maternal death rates approximately 100 times greater than in developed countries.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Both the mother and the father provide care for human offspring, in contrast to other primates, where parental care is mostly done by the mother.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Helpless at birth, humans continue to grow for some years, typically reaching sexual maturity at 15 to 17 years of age.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] The human life span has been split into various stages ranging from three to twelve.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Common stages include infancy, childhood, adolescence, adulthood and old age.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] The lengths of these stages have varied across cultures and time periods but is typified by an unusually rapid growth spurt during adolescence.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Human females undergo menopause and become infertile at around the age of 50.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] It has been proposed that menopause increases a woman's overall reproductive success by allowing her to invest more time and resources in her existing offspring, and in turn their children (the grandmother hypothesis), rather than by continuing to bear children into old age.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] The life span of an individual depends on two major factors, genetics and lifestyle choices.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] For various reasons, including biological/genetic causes, women live on average about four years longer than men.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] As of 2018, the global average life expectancy at birth of a girl is estimated to be 74.9 years compared to 70.4 for a boy.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] There are significant geographical variations in human life expectancy, mostly correlated with economic development – for example, life expectancy at birth in Hong Kong is 87.6 years for girls and 81.8 for boys, while in the Central African Republic, it is 55.0 years for girls and 50.6 for boys.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] The developed world is generally aging, with the median age around 40 years.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] In the developing world, the median age is between 15 and 20 years.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] While one in five Europeans is 60 years of age or older, only one in twenty Africans is 60 years of age or older.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] In 2012, the United Nations estimated that there were 316,600 living centenarians (humans of age 100 or older) worldwide.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Humans are omnivorous, opportunistic feeders capable of consuming a wide variety of plant and animal material.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Human groups have adopted a range of diets from purely vegan to primarily carnivorous.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] In some cases, dietary restrictions in humans can lead to deficiency diseases; however, stable human groups have adapted to many dietary patterns through both genetic specialization and cultural conventions to use nutritionally balanced food sources.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] The human diet is prominently reflected in human culture and has led to the development of food science.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Until the development of agriculture, *Homo sapiens* employed a hunter-gatherer method as their sole means of food collection.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] This involved combining stationary food sources (such as fruits, grains, tubers, and mushrooms, insect larvae and aquatic mollusks) with wild game, which must be hunted and captured in order to be consumed.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] It has been proposed that humans have used fire to prepare and cook food since the time of *Homo erectus*.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Human domestication of wild plants began about 11,700 years ago, leading to the development of agriculture, a gradual process called the Neolithic Revolution.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] These dietary changes may also have altered human biology; the spread of dairy farming provided a new and rich source of food, leading to the evolution of the ability to digest lactose in some adults.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] The types of food consumed, and how they are prepared, have varied widely by time, location, and culture.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] In general, humans can survive for up to eight weeks without food, depending on stored body fat.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Survival without water is usually limited to three or four days, with a maximum of one week.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] In 2020, it was estimated 9 million humans die every year from causes directly or indirectly related to starvation.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Childhood malnutrition is also common and contributes to the global burden of disease.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] However, global food distribution is not even, and obesity among some human populations has increased rapidly, leading to health complications and increased mortality in some developed and a few developing countries.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Worldwide, over one billion people are obese, while in the United States 35% of people are obese, leading to this being described as an "obesity epidemic." Obesity is caused by consuming more calories than are expended, so excessive weight gain is usually caused by an energy-dense diet.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Food consumption is the first step of the digestive process, in which humans ultimately expel feces ranging in frequency from multiple times per day to multiple times per week.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] There is biological variation in the human species – with traits such as blood type, genetic diseases, cranial features, facial features, organ systems, eye color, hair color and texture, height and build, and skin color varying across the globe.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] The typical height of an adult human is between 1.4 and 1.9 m (4 ft 7 in and 6 ft 3 in), although this varies significantly depending on sex, ethnic origin, and family bloodlines.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Body size is partly determined by genes and is also significantly influenced by environmental factors such as diet, exercise, and sleep patterns.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] There is evidence that populations have adapted genetically to various external factors.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] The genes that allow adult humans to digest lactose are present in high frequencies in populations that have long histories of cattle domestication and are more dependent on cow milk.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Sickle cell anemia, which may provide increased resistance to malaria, is frequent in populations where malaria is endemic.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Some populations have evolved highly unique adaptations to very specific environmental conditions, such as those advantageous to ocean-dwelling lifestyles and freediving in the Bajau.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Human hair ranges in color from red to blond to brown to black, which is the most frequent.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Hair color depends on the amount of melanin, with concentrations fading with increased age, leading to grey or even white hair.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Skin color can range from darkest brown to lightest peach, or even nearly white or colorless in cases of albinism.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] It tends to vary clinally and generally correlates with the level of ultraviolet radiation in a particular geographic area, with darker skin mostly around the equator.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Skin darkening may have evolved as protection against ultraviolet solar radiation.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Light skin pigmentation protects against depletion of vitamin D, which requires sunlight to make.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Human skin also has a capacity to darken (tan) in response to exposure to ultraviolet radiation.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] There is relatively little variation between human geographical populations, and most of the variation that occurs is at the individual level.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Much of human variation is continuous, often with no clear points of demarcation.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Genetic data shows that no matter how population groups are defined, two people from the same population group are almost as different from each other as two people from any two different population groups.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Dark-skinned populations that are found in Africa, Australia, and South Asia are not closely related to each other.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Genetic research has demonstrated that human populations native to the African continent are the most genetically diverse and genetic diversity decreases with migratory distance from Africa, possibly the result of bottlenecks during human migration.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] These non-African populations acquired new genetic inputs from local admixture with archaic populations and have much greater variation from Neanderthals and Denisovans than is found in Africa, though Neanderthal admixture into African populations may be underestimated.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Furthermore, recent studies have found that populations in sub-Saharan Africa, and particularly West Africa, have ancestral genetic variation which predates modern humans and has been lost in most non-African populations.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Some of this ancestry is thought to originate from admixture with an unknown archaic hominin that diverged before the split of Neanderthals and modern humans.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Humans are a gonochoric species, meaning they are divided into male and female sexes.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] While the nucleotide genetic variation of individuals of the same sex across global populations is no greater than 0.1%–0.5%, the genetic difference between males and females is between 1% and 2%.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Males on average are 15% heavier and 15 cm (6 in) taller than females.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] On average, males have about 40–50% more upper-body strength and 20–30% more lower-body strength than females at the same weight, due to higher amounts of muscle and larger muscle fibers.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Females generally have a higher body fat percentage than males.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Females have lighter skin than males of the same population; this has been explained by a higher need for vitamin D in females during pregnancy and lactation.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] As there are chromosomal differences between females and males, some X and Y chromosome-related conditions and disorders only affect either males or females.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] After allowing for body weight and volume, the male voice is usually an octave deeper than the female voice.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Females have a longer life span in almost every population around the world.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] There are intersex conditions in the human population, however these are rare.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] The human brain is the locus of "higher" order functioning such as thought, reasoning, and abstraction.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] These cognitive processes constitute the mind, and, along with their behavioral consequences, are studied in the field of psychology.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Humans have a larger and more developed prefrontal cortex than other primates, the region of the brain associated with higher cognition.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] This has led humans to proclaim themselves to be more intelligent than any other known species.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Objectively defining intelligence is difficult, with other animals adapting senses and excelling in areas that humans are unable to.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] There are some traits that, although not strictly unique, do set humans apart from other animals.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Humans may be the only animals who have episodic memory and who can engage in "mental time travel".
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Even compared with other social animals, humans have an unusually high degree of flexibility in their facial expressions.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Humans are the only animals known to cry emotional tears.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Humans are one of the few animals able to self-recognize in mirror tests and there is also debate over to what extent humans are the only animals with a theory of mind.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] The average sleep requirement is between seven and nine hours per day for an adult and nine to ten hours per day for a child; elderly people usually sleep for six to seven hours.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Having less sleep than this is common among humans, even though sleep deprivation can have negative health effects.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] A sustained restriction of adult sleep to four hours per day has been shown to correlate with changes in physiology and mental state, including reduced memory, fatigue, aggression, and bodily discomfort.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] During sleep humans dream, where they experience sensory images and sounds.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Dreaming is stimulated by the pons and mostly occurs during the REM phase of sleep.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] The length of a dream can vary, from a few seconds up to 30 minutes.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Humans have three to five dreams per night, and some may have up to seven.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Dreamers are more likely to remember the dream if awakened during the REM phase.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] The events in dreams are generally outside the control of the dreamer, with the exception of lucid dreaming, where the dreamer is self-aware.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Dreams can at times make a creative thought occur or give a sense of inspiration, as is the case with some notable works of fiction, scientific concepts, and art.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Human consciousness, at its simplest, is sentience or awareness of internal or external existence.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Despite centuries of analyses, definitions, explanations and debates by philosophers and scientists, the underlying nature of consciousness remains enigmatic and poorly understood, being "at once the most familiar and most mysterious aspect of our lives".
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] The only widely agreed notion about the topic is the intuition that it exists.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Opinions differ about what exactly needs to be studied and explained as consciousness.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Some philosophers divide consciousness into phenomenal consciousness, which is sensory experience itself, and access consciousness, which can be used for reasoning or directly controlling actions.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] It is sometimes synonymous with 'the mind', and at other times, an aspect of it.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Historically it is associated with introspection, private thought, imagination and volition.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] It now often includes some kind of experience, cognition, feeling or perception.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] It may be 'awareness', or 'awareness of awareness', or self-awareness.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] There might be different levels or orders of consciousness, or different kinds of consciousness, or just one kind with different features.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] The process of acquiring knowledge and understanding through thought, experience, and the senses is known as cognition.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] The human brain perceives the external world through the senses, and each individual human is influenced greatly by their experiences, leading to subjective views of existence and the passage of time.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] The nature of thought is central to psychology and related fields.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Cognitive psychology studies cognition, the mental processes underlying behavior.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Largely focusing on the development of the human mind through the life span, developmental psychology seeks to understand how people come to perceive, understand, and act within the world and how these processes change as they age.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] This may focus on intellectual, cognitive, neural, social, or moral development.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Psychologists have developed intelligence tests and the concept of intelligence quotient in order to assess the relative intelligence of human beings and study its distribution among population.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Human motivation is not yet wholly understood.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] From a psychological perspective, Maslow's hierarchy of needs is a well-established theory that can be defined as the process of satisfying certain needs in ascending order of complexity.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] From a more general, philosophical perspective, human motivation can be defined as a commitment to, or withdrawal from, various goals requiring the application of human ability.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Furthermore, incentive and preference are both factors, as are any perceived links between incentives and preferences.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Volition may also be involved, in which case willpower is also a factor.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Ideally, both motivation and volition ensure the selection, striving for, and realization of goals in an optimal manner, a function beginning in childhood and continuing throughout a lifetime in a process known as socialization.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Emotions are biological states associated with the nervous system brought on by neurophysiological changes variously associated with thoughts, feelings, behavioral responses, and a degree of pleasure or displeasure.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] They are often intertwined with mood, temperament, personality, disposition, creativity, and motivation.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Emotion has a significant influence on human behavior and their ability to learn.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Acting on extreme or uncontrolled emotions can lead to social disorder and crime, with studies showing criminals may have a lower emotional intelligence than normal.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Emotional experiences perceived as pleasant, such as joy, interest or contentment, contrast with those perceived as unpleasant, like anxiety, sadness, anger, and despair.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Happiness, or the state of being happy, is a human emotional condition.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] The definition of happiness is a common philosophical topic.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Some define it as experiencing the feeling of positive emotional affects, while avoiding the negative ones.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Others see it as an appraisal of life satisfaction or quality of life.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Recent research suggests that being happy might involve experiencing some negative emotions when humans feel they are warranted.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] For humans, sexuality involves biological, erotic, physical, emotional, social, or spiritual feelings and behaviors.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Because it is a broad term, which has varied with historical contexts over time, it lacks a precise definition.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] The biological and physical aspects of sexuality largely concern the human reproductive functions, including the human sexual response cycle.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Sexuality also affects and is affected by cultural, political, legal, philosophical, moral, ethical, and religious aspects of life.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Sexual desire (libido) is a basic mental state present at the beginning of sexual behavior.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Studies have found that men report higher sexual desire than women and masturbate more frequently.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Humans can fall anywhere along a continuous scale of sexual orientation, although most humans are heterosexual.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] While homosexual behavior occurs in some other animals, only humans and domestic sheep have so far been found to exhibit exclusive preference for same-sex relationships.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Most evidence supports nonsocial, biological causes of sexual orientation, as cultures that are very tolerant of homosexuality do not have significantly higher rates of it.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Research in neuroscience and genetics suggests that other aspects of human sexuality are biologically influenced as well.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] Love most commonly refers to a feeling of strong attraction or emotional attachment.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] It can be impersonal (the love of an object, ideal, or strong political or spiritual connection) or interpersonal (love between humans).
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] In the emotional state of romantic love, neurochemicals such as dopamine, norepinephrine, serotonin, and oxytocin stimulate the brain's reward system through the mesocorticolimbic pathway (MCL).
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p01] This dopaminergic pathway may result in side effects such as tachycardia (increased heart rate), loss of appetite, insomnia (sleeplessness), and intense euphoria.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] Humanity's unprecedented set of intellectual skills were a key factor in the species' eventual technological advancement and concomitant domination of the biosphere.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] Disregarding extinct hominids, humans are the only animals known to teach generalizable information, innately deploy recursive embedding to generate and communicate complex concepts, engage in the "folk physics" required for competent tool design, or cook food in the wild.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] Teaching and learning preserves the cultural and ethnographic identity of human societies.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] Other traits and behaviors that are mostly unique to humans include starting fires, phoneme structuring and vocal learning.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] While many species communicate, language is unique to humans, a defining feature of humanity, and a cultural universal.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] Unlike the limited communication-systems of other animals, human language is open – an infinite number of meanings can be produced by combining a limited number of symbols.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] Human language also has the capacity of displacement, using words to represent things and happenings that are not presently or locally occurring but reside in the shared imagination of interlocutors.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] Language differs from other forms of communication in that it is modality independent; people can convey the same meanings through different media: audibly in speech, visually by sign language or writing, and through tactile media such as braille.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] Language is central to communication between humans, and to the sense of identity that can unite nations, cultures and ethnic groups.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] As of 1996 humans used approximately six thousand different languages, including sign languages, and many thousands more are extinct.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] Human arts can take many forms including visual, literary, and performing.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] Visual art can range from paintings and sculptures to film, fashion design, and architecture.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] Literary arts can include prose, poetry, and dramas.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] The performing arts generally involve theater, music, and dance.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] Humans often combine the different forms (for example, music videos).
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] Other entities that have been described as having artistic qualities include food preparation, video games, and medicine.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] As well as providing entertainment and transferring knowledge, the arts are also used for political purposes.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] Art is a defining characteristic of humans and there is evidence for a relationship between creativity and language.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] The earliest evidence of art was shell engravings made by *Homo erectus* 300,000 years before modern humans evolved.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] Art attributed to *H. sapiens* existed at least 75,000 years ago, with jewelry and drawings found in caves in South Africa.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] There are various hypotheses as to why humans have adapted to the arts.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] These include allowing them to better problem solve issues, providing a means to control or influence other humans, encouraging cooperation and contribution within a society or increasing the chance of attracting a potential mate.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] The use of imagination developed through art, combined with logic may have given early humans an evolutionary advantage.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] Evidence of humans engaging in musical activities predates cave art and so far music has been practiced by virtually all known human cultures.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] There exists a wide variety of music genres and ethnic musics; with humans' musical abilities being related to other abilities, including complex social human behaviors.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] It has been shown that human brains respond to music by becoming synchronized with the rhythm and beat, a process called entrainment.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] Dance is also a form of human expression found in all cultures and may have evolved as a way to help early humans communicate.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] Listening to music and observing dance stimulates the orbitofrontal cortex and other pleasure sensing areas of the brain.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] Unlike speaking, reading and writing does not come naturally to humans and must be taught.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] Still, literature has been present before the invention of words and language, with 30,000-year-old paintings on walls inside some caves portraying a series of dramatic scenes.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] One of the oldest surviving works of literature is the *Epic of Gilgamesh*, first engraved on ancient Babylonian tablets about 4,000 years ago.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] Beyond simply passing down knowledge, the use and sharing of imaginative fiction through stories might have helped develop humans' capabilities for communication and increased the likelihood of securing a mate.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] Storytelling may also be used as a way to provide the audience with moral lessons and encourage cooperation.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] Stone tools were used by proto-humans at least 2.5 million years ago.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] The use and manufacture of tools has been put forward as the ability that defines humans more than anything else and has historically been seen as an important evolutionary step.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] The technology became much more sophisticated about 1.8 million years ago, with the controlled use of fire beginning around 1 million years ago.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] The wheel and wheeled vehicles appeared simultaneously in several regions some time in the fourth millennium BC.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] The development of more complex tools and technologies allowed land to be cultivated and animals to be domesticated, thus proving essential in the development of agriculture – what is known as the Neolithic Revolution.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] China developed paper, the printing press, gunpowder, the compass and other important inventions.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] The continued improvements in smelting allowed forging of copper, bronze, iron and eventually steel, which is used in railways, skyscrapers and many other products.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] This coincided with the Industrial Revolution, where the invention of automated machines brought major changes to humans' lifestyles.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] Definitions of religion vary; according to one definition, a religion is a belief system concerning the supernatural, sacred or divine, and practices, values, institutions and rituals associated with such belief.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] The evolution and the history of the first religions have become areas of active scientific investigation.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] Credible evidence of religious behavior dates to the Middle Paleolithic era (45–200 thousand years ago).
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] It may have evolved to play a role in helping enforce and encourage cooperation between humans.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] Religion can include a belief in life after death, the origin of life, the nature of the universe (religious cosmology) and its ultimate fate (eschatology), and moral or ethical teachings.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] Views on transcendence and immanence vary substantially; traditions variously espouse monism, deism, pantheism, and theism (including polytheism and monotheism).
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] Although measuring religiosity is difficult, a majority of humans profess some variety of religious or spiritual belief.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] In 2015 the plurality were Christian followed by Muslims, Hindus and Buddhists.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] As of 2015, about 16%, or slightly under 1.2 billion humans, were irreligious, including those with no religious beliefs or no identity with any religion.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] A defining attribute of humanity is the capacity for cumulative cultural evolution by transmitting knowledge across generations by continuously building on past knowledge to develop tools, scientific laws and other advancements to pass on to future generations.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] This accumulated knowledge can be tested to answer various questions or make predictions about how the universe functions, driving ongoing human advancement.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] Aristotle has been described as the first scientist, and preceded the rise of scientific thought through the Hellenistic period.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] Other early advances in science came from the Han dynasty in China and during the Islamic Golden Age.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] The scientific revolution, near the end of the Renaissance, led to the emergence of modern science.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] A chain of events and influences led to the development of the scientific method, a process of observation and experimentation that is used to differentiate science from pseudoscience.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] An understanding of mathematics is unique to humans, although other species of animals have some numerical cognition.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] Philosophy is a field of study where humans seek to understand fundamental truths about themselves and the world in which they live.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] Philosophical inquiry has been a major feature in the development of humans' intellectual history.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] It has been described as the "no man's land" between definitive scientific knowledge and dogmatic religious teachings.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] Major fields of philosophy include metaphysics, epistemology, logic, and axiology (which includes ethics and aesthetics).
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] Society is the system of organizations and institutions arising from interaction between humans.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] Humans are highly social and tend to live in large complex social groups.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] They can be divided into different groups according to their income, wealth, power, reputation and other factors.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] The structure of social stratification and the degree of social mobility differs, especially between modern and traditional societies.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] Human groups range from the size of families to nations.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] The first form of human social organization is thought to have resembled hunter-gatherer band societies.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] Human societies typically exhibit gender identities and gender roles that distinguish between masculine and feminine characteristics and prescribe the range of acceptable behaviors and attitudes for their members based on their sex.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] The most common categorization is a gender binary of men and women.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] Some societies recognize a third gender, or less commonly a fourth or fifth.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] In some other societies, non-binary is used as an umbrella term for a range of gender identities that are not solely male or female.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] Gender roles are often associated with a division of norms, practices, dress, behavior, rights, duties, privileges, status, and power, with men enjoying more rights and privileges than women in most societies, both today and in the past.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] As a social construct, gender roles are not fixed and vary historically within a society.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] Challenges to predominant gender norms have recurred in many societies.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] Little is known about gender roles in the earliest human societies.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] Early modern humans probably had a range of gender roles similar to that of modern cultures from at least the Upper Paleolithic, while the Neanderthals were less sexually dimorphic and there is evidence that the behavioral difference between males and females was minimal.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] All human societies organize, recognize and classify types of social relationships based on relations between parents, children and other descendants (consanguinity), and relations through marriage (affinity).
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] There is also a third type applied to godparents or adoptive children (fictive).
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] These culturally defined relationships are referred to as kinship.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] In many societies, it is one of the most important social organizing principles and plays a role in transmitting status and inheritance.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] All societies have rules of incest taboo, according to which marriage between certain kinds of kin relations is prohibited, and some also have rules of preferential marriage with certain kin relations.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] Pair bonding is a ubiquitous feature of human sexual relationships, whether it is manifested as serial monogamy, polygyny, or polyandry.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] Genetic evidence indicates that humans were predominantly polygynous for most of their existence as a species, but that this began to shift during the Neolithic, when monogamy started becoming widespread concomitantly with the transition from nomadic to sedentary societies.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] Anatomical evidence in the form of second-to-fourth digit ratios, a biomarker for prenatal androgen effects, likewise indicates modern humans were polygynous during the Pleistocene.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] Human ethnic groups are a social category that identifies together as a group based on shared attributes that distinguish them from other groups.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] These can be a common set of traditions, ancestry, language, history, society, culture, nation, religion, or social treatment within their residing area.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] Ethnicity is separate from the concept of race, which is based on physical characteristics, although both are socially constructed.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] Assigning ethnicity to a certain population is complicated, as even within common ethnic designations there can be a diverse range of subgroups, and the makeup of these ethnic groups can change over time at both the collective and individual level.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] Also, there is no generally accepted definition of what constitutes an ethnic group.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] Ethnic groupings can play a powerful role in the social identity and solidarity of ethnopolitical units.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] This has been closely tied to the rise of the nation state as the predominant form of political organization in the 19th and 20th centuries.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] As farming populations gathered in larger and denser communities, interactions between these different groups increased.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] This led to the development of governance within and between the communities.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] Humans have evolved the ability to change affiliation with various social groups relatively easily, including previously strong political alliances, if doing so is seen as providing personal advantages.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] This cognitive flexibility allows individual humans to change their political ideologies, with those with higher flexibility less likely to support authoritarian and nationalistic stances.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] Governments create laws and policies that affect the citizens that they govern.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] There have been many forms of government throughout human history, each having various means of obtaining power and the ability to exert diverse controls on the population.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] Approximately 47% of humans live in some form of a democracy, 17% in a hybrid regime, and 37% in an authoritarian regime.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] Many countries belong to international organizations and alliances; the largest of these is the United Nations, with 193 member states.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] Trade, the voluntary exchange of goods and services, is seen as a characteristic that differentiates humans from other animals and has been cited as a practice that gave *Homo sapiens* a major advantage over other hominids.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] Evidence suggests early *H. sapiens* made use of long-distance trade routes to exchange goods and ideas, leading to cultural explosions and providing additional food sources when hunting was sparse, while such trade networks did not exist for the now extinct Neanderthals.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] Early trade likely involved materials for creating tools like obsidian.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] The first truly international trade routes were around the spice trade through the Roman and medieval periods.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] Early human economies were more likely to be based around gift giving instead of a bartering system.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] Early money consisted of commodities; the oldest being in the form of cattle and the most widely used being cowrie shells.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] Money has since evolved into governmental issued coins, paper and electronic money.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] Human study of economics is a social science that looks at how societies distribute scarce resources among different people.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] There are massive inequalities in the division of wealth among humans; the eight richest humans are worth the same monetary value as the poorest half of all the human population.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] Humans commit violence on other humans at a rate comparable to other primates, but have an increased preference for killing adults, infanticide being more common among other primates.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] Phylogenetic analysis predicts that 2% of early *H. sapiens* would be murdered, rising to 12% during the medieval period, before dropping to below 2% in modern times.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] There is great variation in violence between human populations, with rates of homicide about 0.01% in societies that have legal systems and strong cultural attitudes against violence.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] The willingness of humans to kill other members of their species en masse through organized conflict (i.e., war) has long been the subject of debate.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] One school of thought holds that war evolved as a means to eliminate competitors, and has always been an innate human characteristic.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] Another suggests that war is a relatively recent phenomenon and has appeared due to changing social conditions.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] War has had a high cost on human life; it is estimated that during the 20th century, between 167 million and 188 million people died as a result of war.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] War casualty data is less reliable for pre-medieval times, especially global figures.
[src:e-coli/h-sapiens-p02] But compared with any period over the past 600 years, the past 80 years (post-1945) has seen a very significant drop in global military and civilian death rates due to armed conflict.
